For work, my primary driver is I view technology as fundamentally a positive motive force for humanity (in terms of quality of life, health, economics, opportunity etc) and I want to be involved with important technologies and technology companies and trends

But there tend to be rings of impact in life:
-Work and study (me me me)
-Personal life / family (us us us)
-Community (bigger us us us)
-Society (everyone everyone everyone)

And for each of these there are different drivers, motivators etc

Things that are important for AI products:
-Ship fast & iterate
-No GPU before product/market fit (in most cases, not all)
-Build for a specific user or customer

The misconceptions tend to be the opposite of these

-Focus on context, not generic advice, although sometimes generic is correct

-Focus on what people are really asking, versus words they are saying. Uncomfortable topics in particular tend to get avoided and you need to ease these out into the open

-Cut to the most important thing, not all the ancillary

-Move to a major tech center / cluster (SF, NY, London, etc)

-Join for any role - get into the main company vs optimize for role
-Seek great networks, worry less about comp early in career
